fields.descriptive_line: Boxed set of sixty colour prints, Macmillan's History Class Pictures Set 2, England, 1951
fields.physical_description:
Dark red portfolio holding sixty colour printed sheets, inside a green paper folder.
[61.	An Early Printing Works] Colour print with plain border, depicting a busy printer's workshop. On the left, compositors prepare type for inking. In the foreground on the right, a large press is operated while the patron looks on. The image includes a wealth of detail on the mechanisms and materials of Early Modern printmaking.
[62.	Three Notable Ships] Colour print with plain border, depicting three ships in a rolling seascape of bright turquoise waves under a bright blue sky. The three ships represent the Santa Maria, from Columbus's fleet, HMS Sirius, the first steamer to cross the Atlantic, and the 1939 Ocean liner Queen Elizabeth. All three are shown sailing at full speed, with billowing sails and smoking chimneys. The style is very graphic; the pattern of light and foam on the water is depicted in simple fields of solid colour reminiscent of woodcuts.
[63.	The Tower & London Bridge] Colour print with plain border, depicting a view of the White Tower and its inhabitants, with the City of London in the background. The birds-eye view shows the River Thames curving around the Tower, which is full of knights on horseback, and gathering in the hall in front of the king. The perspective of the image is flattened and scale is distorted in a style reminiscent of sixteenth century art.
[64.	Reading the Great Bible Tudor Times] Colour print with plain border, depicting a group of wealthy people gathered around a man reading from a large book. The group includes children and adults, women and men, and they all stand or sit calmly listening. The scene is set in a shadowy crypt, and the colours are rich jewel tones.
[65.	Henry VIII Giving the Charter to the Barber-Surgeons] Colour print with plain border, depicting Henry VIII sitting on a wodden chair, on a red carpet, in front of a hanging tapestry. Henry wears an ermine-lined red cape over a purple knee-length tunic. On both sides of him are rows of kneeling Barber-surgeons, dressed in red trimmed cloaks and black caps. They all look toward the King as he hands over a small piece of paper.
[66.	May-Day Revels] Colour print with plain border, depicting a colourful group in a gelntly sloping valley, dancing around a May pole. The crowd includes a monk in a brown habit, drummers and pipers, and fools in costume. The pole is adorned with ribbons and wrapped with foliage. A white church and large manor house can be seen in the distance.
[67.	Busy Cooks, Tudor Times] Colour print with plain border, depicting a tiled kitchen with a large hearth and roaring fire. Three women roast chickens on spits. There are unprepared birds and hares on every surface. On the right, a boy carries a rack of ribs on a tray to a table of four men in the background. There is high key lighting acorss the picture, with the fire as the main light source.
[68.	A Play in an Inn Yard] Colour print with plain border, depicting a makeshift stage in a galleried courtyard. The audience is seated on two benches and gathered on the balcony, watching two men and a woman performing in front of yellow and white curtains. The men are dressed in doublets and hose, and dogs roll around on the cobbled floor.
[69.	St Paul’s Cathedral, the Bear Garden & the Globe Theatre] Colour print with plain border, depicting a bird's eye across the River Thames from a vantage point South of the river. In the foreground, the tall stone structures are set among trees, and are surrounded by crowds. The river is also busy,with large sailing ships and small ferries. The large square tower of St Paul's Cathedral stands on the other shore, rising out of densely built city of red roofs, spires, and windmills.
[70.	A Bagmaker’s Shop] Colour print with plain border, depicting two rooms of a bagmakers shop. On the left, in the back room, three men busily make small bags, which take the form of gathered pouches with decorative drawstrings. Animal pelts hang on the wall behind, as one man cuts the pieces and two others sew them up. On the wall hang a range of embroidered and embellished finished products. On the right hand side, a woman serves a couple who have come with their dog. The wife holds a red bag she has chosen, while the husband stands with hand on hip, handing over the money. More beaded and tassled bags hang on the wall behind.
[71.	Queen Elizabeth’s Coach] Colour print with plain border, depicting Queen Elizabeth I in a gold coach with pink plumes, surrounded by an entourage of running attendants, dogs, and horses. They travel along a dusty road through a green field. The sky is bright blue and all the colours are heightened. The artist has signe dthe picture with the note 'after an engraving'. This is probably Joris Hoefnagel's print of Queen Elizabeth arriving at Nonesuch Palace, from 1582, which shows the queen in a similar pose, with a rearing horse behind.
[72.	Explorers in an Indian Village] Colour print with plain border, depicting the meeting of Europeans and Native Americans on a hillside. A woven mat on the floor marks the place of a meeting between leaders, while groups stand on either side. The Europeans hold guns, swords and spears, while the indigenous inhabitants, who can be seen in a large army in the middle ground, have bows and arrows. An enclosed village can be seen on the plain below, alongside a European ship flying a St George's cross. The representation of the Native Americans is stereotyped; there is an atmosphere of confusion created by the criss-crossing gazes of all the figures involved.
[73.	An Elizabethan Theatre] Colour print with plain border, depicting a performance in a large open theatre. The stage is under a tiled canopy, held up on ionic columns. A large audience watches from the stalls and three tiers of boxes. The viewpoint is one of these boxes, and in the foreground three men and boy can be seen shouting and cheering. On stage, two characters have a sword fight. Figures are quite caricatured, with exaggerated facial features and very bright colours.
[74.	A Royal Picnic] Colour print with plain border, depicting a garden full of revelling courtiers. In the centre, to the left, Queen Elizabeth sits in front of a cloth laid on the grass, filled with plates of meat. In front, waiters serve more large dishes of poultry, younger boys drink from golden jugs, and groups of bearded men relax on the grass. The overall atmosphere is one of festive indulgence.
[75.	Queen Elizabeth Going in Procession] Colour print with plain border, depicting Queen Elizabeth I, in a yellow dress, being drawin through the main street of a tonw on a gilded carriage with pink canopy. She is surrounded by male couriters walking and horseback. The artist has signed the picture and added 'after an engraving'.
[76.	Merry-Making, Tudor Times] Colour print with plain border, depicting a crowded hall, full of raucous acrobats, actors and animals. A balcony of musicians in matching liveries accompanies overhead. A boy in the foreground sits astride a man in a crocodile costume, and a jester in striped tights dances into the frame. The audience stands against the walls around the edges. The style is exaggerated and cartoon-like, with high key colours and lighting, and dark shadows.
[77.	Village Life, Tudor Times] Colour print with plain border, depicting a village in the snow. In the centre stands a church on small hill. Couples walk down to the cottages, where figures chop wood, gather sticks, deliver bread and play with children.
[78.	Gentleman and Attendants Hawking] Colour print with plain border, depicting three figures on a hillside. The landscape they are in is lush and verdant, with a river flowing through the wooded valley and a thatched cottage on the left. The gentleman, in gold and red doublet and blue hose, holds a hawk on his outstretched arm. Behind, two other men look into the distance. There are four dogs sniffing around their feet.
[79.	Departure of the “Mayflower”] Colour print with plain border, depicting a boat full of people being rowed out to sea, towards a large ship. On shore, a crowd watches their departure with trepidation. The picture uses a limited palette of blues and greys, and the figures are dressed in puritan outfits of black and white. The large Mayflower is rigged with many sails and looms imposingly on the horizon.
[80.	Charles 1 Saying Farewell to Two of His Children] Colour print with plain border, depicting King Charles I, dressed in blue with a white lace collar, bending to embrace his son Prince Charles, wearing purple and gold. Queen Henrietta Maria, crying, comforts Princess Henrietta. Behind, three soldiers stand waiting to take to Charles to his execution. The scenes takes place in a richly furnished hall with velvet chair and tiled floor.
[81.	An Army on the March] Colour print with plain border, depicting a Roundhead army walking in formation through a ruined landscape. They are arranged three abreast, and hold guns over their shoulders. Destroyed trees and carriages lie alongside the road, as they approach a stone building that may be a castle.
[82.	Boys’ Sports] Colour print with plain border, depicting a large group of well-dressed boys in a yard. The activities include stilt-walking, spinning tops, throwing a ball for a dog, playing chequers, blowing darts, running with a hoop, playing on a swing, riding a hobby horse and playing skittles. The boys all have fashionable long hair, and are laughing and smiling. 
[83.	A Fire-Engine] Colour print with plain border, depicting a group of men operating a fire engine to put out a fire in a town. The low angle of the picture looks up to the vehicle, which is being filled with water while more men pump the jet of water being pointed into the blaze. On the left, townspeople look frightened out of their windows. The image has a limited palette of red, orange and black, and has a tense, dramatic atmosphere.
[84.	Tetbury Market Place] Colour print with plain border, depicting a large open space in the centre of the town. There are several carts parked to the left, and a number of tradespeople in the foreground, but the main part of the cobbled square is open and empty. It is surrounded by houses with pitched roofs and covered walkways.
[85.	A Fashionable Surgeon] Colour print with plain border, depicting a richly decorated room, with portraits on the wall and a number of tables around the walls. At the centre, a woman in a red dress sits on a chair while the surgeon, is dark green silk, ties a tourniquet around her upper arm. Two attendants hold plates and bowls ready.
[86.	A Shooting Party] Colour print with plain border, depicting a group of men hunting pheasants in an autumn landscape. They face away from the viewer towards a group of seven birds taken flight. There are two men on horseback with rifles, two on foot following, a number of dogs, and another group of hunters in the distance. There is a large house on the horizon.
[87.	Poultry Stalls] Colour print with plain border, depicting a row of market stalls in the centre of a colourful town. On the left, a man shows off swans, geese and a peacock hanging from his awning. In the centre of the square is a woman plucking a bird into a basket of feathers, a man handling chickens, a row of geese and a group of customers looking at the poultry. The scene is brightly lit and all are wearing brightly coloured clothes.
[88.	A Lace & Book Shop] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of a well-stocked shop. The shelves on the left are filled with leather bound volumes. On the right, the shelves behind the counter are piled with lace-trimmed handkerchiefs, fans and gloves. There are six customers browsing the wares, all fashionably dressed in bright silks.
[89.	A Boot & Shoe Shop] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of a shop. Three men sit in the centre, making up shoes, which are given in pieces by a man standing on the left. Behind him, a woman draws out thread. A row of boots and shoes in a range of colours hangs above their heads, in front of a trellis and workbench.
[90.	A Children’s Playroom in a Gentleman’s House] Colour print with plain border, depicting a sunlit paved terrace and seven idealised children wearing satin, silk and lace. They range from baby to about 10 years old, and have a variety of games and toys, including a windmill, doll, and pop-gun. The partially covered space is tiled in marble and there are paintings of a hunting scene on the wall. On the left and right beyond balustrades can be seen a green garden.
[91.	A Small School] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of a private school for upper class children. On the left, a teacher with a long grey beard and wide-brimmed hat, sitting on a low platform, checks the work of a young boy is blue and yellow satin. There is a queue behind him of others waiting for guidance. At the back, a trellis table is surrounded by seven boys standing to work. A group of girls in the foreground talk and play games.
[92.	A Charity School] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of a sparsely furnished charity school. The single point perspective emphasises the length of the room and the smallness of the children, who sit in two rows down the edge of the room. The teacher, in a black top hat, sits at the back of the room behind a desk. On the panelled walls are pinned various posters used for teaching, and a fire burns in a grate on the left,
[93.	The Interior of a Coffee House] Colour print with plain border, depicting a large, open interior inhabited by many fashionable men in long, curled wigs. They are drinking coffee from wide, shallow mugs and smoking white clay pipes. The waiters are dressed in matching uniforms and white aprons. There is a fire in one corner of the room and a number of female portraits hanging on the walls.
[94.	A Barber & Wigmaker’s Shop] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of a well-lit barbers shop. In the centre, a man is being shaved, while all around men and women put together and dress wigs at various stages of manufacture. A selection of wigs hangs on the back wall. The floor is covered with red tiles and there are two large windows on the left hand wall.
[95.	The Taj Mahal] Colour print with plain border, depicting the central dome and towers of the Taj Mahal, and two ornamental ponds in front. The sky is loosely washed in blue and yellow, and a number of figures are loosely sketched in the foreground.
[96.	The Attack on Quebec] Colour print with plain border, depicting a birds-eye view of an army arriving by boat, scrambling up an embankment to a flat battlefield. The arriving soldiers are dressed in red and fly St George's and Union flags, and meet a standing army dressed in blue. A landscape of rolling hills stretches into the distance, ander a sky of rolling grey clouds.
[97.	A Post-Chaise & A Sedan Chair] Colour print with plain border, depicting a street scene in a smart Georgian town. On the left, a carriage with four horses is parked outside a neo-classical building, while a woman is carried in a small pink litter across the street from the right. Other figures ride and walk across the clean, paved road.
[98.	How the Americans Declared their Independence] Colour print with plain border, depicting a crowded street scene. A man in the centre, on horseback, reads from a scroll, while the people around cheer and wave their hats. The colours are bright, with long violet shadows across the uneven floor. 
[99.	A Goods Wagon & A London Mail-Coach] Colour print with plain border, depicting two carriages crossing on a dusty country road, by an inn. The shiny black and red London Bristol mail coach speeds by on the left, with a man sitting on the back blowing a long horn. On the right, the driver of the covered goods wagon waves his hat. His horses are heavy and his wagon has large wheels. A woman and a pile of boxes can be seen under the canopy.
[100.	Spinning, Weaving & Dyeing Cloth] Colour print with plain border, depicting three separate scenes in the preparation of cloth. On the top left, a blonde woman sits in a doorway, operating a spinning wheel. On the top left, a man works at a loom. At the bottom, a group of men dye the cloth in large wooden vats, and a man in a suit folds the finished bolts.
[101.	London Street Cries - A] Colour print with plain border, depicting two street scenes. On the left, a woman with a large basket on her head is captioned 'Strawberries, scarlet Strawberries!'. On the right, a woman carrying a yoke, beside two large silver pails, offers milk to two street children. The caption is 'Milk below, Maids!'
[102.	London Street Cries - B] Colour print with plain border, depicting two scenes of tradespeople. On the left, two women bring chairs to a seated man, who is repairing their woven seats, with the caption 'Old chairs to mend!'. On the right, a group by the side of a portico examine cherries in some scales, with the caption 'Sweet cherries, round and sound!'
[103.	A Slave Sale in Virginia] Colour print with plain border, depicting the interior of an auction room. A black man, woman and baby stand on a stage next to an auctioneer, in front of a room of white men wearing frock coats and hats. There are posters around the walls advertising sales and runaway slaves.
[104.	A Stage-Coach & Turnpike] Colour print with plain border, depicting a coach with four horses, full of people rattling along a country lane, through rolling green hills. The four dappled grey horses are approaching a white five-bar gate across the road, where a toll keeper waits their arrival.
[105.	The Aqueduct on the Bridgewater Canal at Barton] Colour print with plain border, depicting a barge travelling across an aquaduct over a river. The bridge is buit of brick and has three wide pointed arches. There is a family on the riverbank, pointing at the barge. 
[106.	The Montgolfiers’ Hot-Air Balloon] Colour print with plain border, depicting the launch of a large, gold and turquoise hot air balloon. The scene is a formal ornamental garden, filled with a well-dressed audience of men and women. There is a large platform with a fire in the centre, and the balloon is held down by four men pulling on ropes.
[107.	The Pit-Head of a Coal Mine] Colour print with plain border, depicting an industrial scene of machinery and workers with donkeys and horses. The subdued palette of brown and grey creates a barren atmosphere, as a group shovel and carry coal. A brick chimney pumps out smoke and green-tinged structures support cranes and winches.
[108.	A Cast-Iron Bridge Over the Wear at Sunderland] Colour print with plain border, depicting the construction of a large, wide span bridge. Two pillars of wooden scaffold rise from the river to support a arc of iron and with a green railing. The piers on either side of the bridge are made of light coloured blocks of stone. A large ship approaches the bridge. 
[109.	Rush Bearing] Colour print with plain border, depicting a parade of people carrying budles of rushes into a church. They are dressed simply, the women in brightly coloured dresses with white caps, and the men in cream-coloured jackets. Children carry large orange flags among the group. They are observed by a group of gentry in more formal clothing.
[110.	A Turnspit in an Inn Kitchen] Colour print with plain border, depicting the warm interior of an inn. On the left, a haunch of meat turns on a spit, and a woman sits and watches it. Two groups of visitors sit on the right on large wooden tables and benches. The furnishings are sparse and simple.
[111.	Smugglers Loading up the Ponies] Colour print with plain border, depicting a man pulling two small ponies up a steep path. The ponies have cartons and barrels roped onto their backs. Down on the beach, a small boat unloads onto a worn, stony quay, where more ponies wait.
[112.	Napoleon’s Army for the Invasion of England] Colour print with plain border, depicting a high angle view across a yellow sandy beach and bright blue sea. The landscape is filled with marching armies in bright red uniform, a number of cavalry units, and the sea is populated by boats with bright white sails. 
[113.	Hyde Park on a Sunday] Colour print with plain border, depicting a colourful and lively scene of crowds in Hyde Park. There are children playing, couples promenading, and entertainers at work. In the background, horses are grazing in the open field, and carriages come and go. The atmosphere is bustling and comical.
[114.	The Opening of the Stockton & Darlington Railway] Colour print with plain border, depicting a crowd by the side of a railway, watching a steam train with open-topped coaches speeding along the track behind a white horse. The crowd, who are in shadow, wave and cheer, and some horses are spooked. The train on the tracks has an orange engine and trails a thick plume of dark grey smoke.
[115.	An Early Steam Carriage] Colour print with plain border, depicting a black and red steam carriage driving down a sandy road, watched by a crowded pavement of onlookers. The driver of the carriage sits at the front, holding a black steering wheel, there are about ten passengers. There are clouds of dust around the wheels. A man with a dog runs alongside the carriage.
[116.	The Launching of the ‘Great Britain’ at Bristol] Colour print with plain border, depicting huge crowds around Bristol harbour, cheering the launch of a large black, red and white ship festooned with flags. 
[117.	Ploughing, Rolling & Sowing Broadcast] Colour print with plain border, depicting a large group of men and horses preparing a field. A group of horse pulls a plough, anotehr group a harrow, and then two men scatter seeds. They are set in a gently rolling, russet landscape of fenced fields of sheep with chalky outcrops and patches of woodland.
[118.	Australian Settlers receive News from Home] Colour print with plain border, depicting five men reading letters and newspapers in a wooden shelter. They are surrounded by guns, crockery, clothing, animals, horse tack and blankets. They are cheerful and relaxed. Out of the doorway can be a seen a wide, flat landscape full of sheep.
[119.	The ‘Lady of the Lamp’ receiving Wounded Soldiers at the Hospital] Colour print with plain border, depicting Florence Nightingale standing in the doorway of a stone building, receiving wounded soldiers who are hobbling and being carried on stretchers. There are two other female nurses assisting the men. Nightingale wears a wide grey dress and red bow tie.
[120.	A Promenade in the Pantiles, Tunbridge Wells] Colour print with plain border, depicting fashionable young women in the shopping district of Tunbridge Wells. In the foreground, a young woman wearing a wide crinoline approaches a man selling coloured balloons. 
[Box] Large red portfolio, opening at one end, with stapled sides. The inside of the flap features a paper label, listing all the images in the series.

fields.public_access_description: This set of History Class Pictures was produced by educational publishers  Macmillan in 1951. It features sixty full colour illustrations, tracing British history, with some global exceptions, from Tudor times to 1855.  Drawn by a range of artists, the images make reference to famous events and inventions, reinterpreted in a bright and often humorous style meant  to engage children. The grand narrative view they offer of history is told through the everyday anecdotes of shops and streets, as well as war and technological revolution.
fields.bibliography: Joris Hoefnagel, Queen Elizabeth Arriving at Nonesuch Palace, Engraving, 1582
fields.history_note: The two sets of History Class Pictures (B.401 and 402-2012) were found in Ralph Munn's loft when he died in 1995. Munns was a history teacher in the early 1960s, and he used these pictures to teach junior aged children.
